1134. To SEBASTIAN RoTENHAN.

Epistolae ad diuersos p. 557. Louvain. HN : Lond. xiv. 24 : LB. 521. 13 August 1520.

[The year-date is confirmed by the mention of Erasmus* reply to Lec : see Ep. 1061 intilod. In August 1521, the only other year possxble, he was at Anderlec lt.

Sebastian Rotenhan (Rubrigallus) of Rentweinsdorf, 10 ms. N. of Bamberg *51478—0. 25 June 1532), was of noble birth. He matriculated at Erfurt in the summer of 1493, and on 2 Feb. 1496 at Ingolstadt. From 1499 to 1504 he studied law at Bologna ; where in 1501—2 he was Proctor of the German nation, and in 15oo-1 delivered an oration to the nation which was copied into their Acta (ANGB. p. 254). He was a pupil of Philip Beroaldus (Ep. 256. 13711), who mentions him in the preface to an edition of Gellius, Bologna, Bened. Hectoris, 1 Feb. 1503. His doctor’s degree in law he took at siena, 31 Oct. 1503.

On returning to Gerniany he became an assessor in the Imperial Chaneery, 1507. A letter from him to Sebastian Erant, dated NVorms, 14 July 1511 (see J. Wenckerv Culicem arclzfm' *im-a, 1715, p. 142) and asking for mss. of medieval chroniclers, shows that he was already interested in the history of Germany. About 1512 he began tmvelling, to Spain, Franco, and England ; and on 25 Sept? 1514 was created Kt. of the Holy Sepulchra at Jerusalem. In Eck's Orationes tres, Augsburg. Miller, 5 Dee. 1515, f0. B4‚ he is mentioued as one of the glories of Germmy, ‘in Imperiali consistorio inter eruditissimos iudicatus’.
